00:00:25.878 --> 00:00:29.320
PROFESSOR: I'll do
the Vanna White thing.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:34.340
So this sucks in air
here, and inside,

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:39.040
57% of methane or other
combustible gases in it.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:43.330
And it sucks in about I
think half liter a minute.

00:00:43.330 --> 00:00:45.900
And so you can get a
percent gas in the air.

00:00:45.900 --> 00:00:50.200
And so luckily, at the moment,
there's probably 0% methane.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:53.410
AUDIENCE: Is that what
gas companies quickly

00:00:53.410 --> 00:00:54.160
use to find leaks?

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:55.660
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
yeah, they normally

00:00:55.660 --> 00:00:56.750
have a big probe on it.

00:00:56.750 --> 00:01:00.005
And what they do is they
take bang bar, which

00:01:00.005 --> 00:01:02.130
is like a big stick and
they stick it in the ground

00:01:02.130 --> 00:01:04.060
until they get a
hole, and then they

00:01:04.060 --> 00:01:07.250
stick this with a probe
on it, suck air in

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:10.100
and figure out what the
percent gas is in the soil.

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:12.120
Then they know by where
the highest percentage

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:13.175
is in the soil.

00:01:13.175 --> 00:01:15.300
They figure, OK, that's
probably where the leak is,

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.180
and they start digging there.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:25.068
So it's a really simple
and fantastic tool.

00:01:25.068 --> 00:01:27.550
CGI, yeah, combustible
gas indicator.

00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:32.850
PROFESSOR: And right here
is where the inlet is,

00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:34.350
OK, just off of here.

00:01:34.350 --> 00:01:39.000
We do this-- it's better to
do it than in the back bumper,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.010
because there can be some
exhaust contamination.

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:49.740
Actually, well, two cars, we've
tested it, do not interfere,

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.720
but this is a little
bit of an old van.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:55.520
So sometimes-- I mean, it
passed the emissions test,

00:01:55.520 --> 00:02:00.370
but still there can
be some contamination.

00:02:00.370 --> 00:02:04.030
That's why when we
stopped, sometimes you'll

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:07.600
get some measurements, but
when you're moving forward

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:11.710
and the wind is upstream, you
know you're getting readings.

00:02:11.710 --> 00:02:14.440
This is the methane
reading that analyzers

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.720
are reading right now.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.310
So it's anything below
2, it's right now,

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:23.690
1.96 is pretty clean.

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:25.660
There's no leak where
we are right now.

00:02:25.660 --> 00:02:31.510
So if it's under 2, you know
we're in a place with no leak.

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:36.720
And even if it creeps up over
2, if it's like 2.01, 2.02,

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.330
that's not really
indicative of a leak.

00:02:40.330 --> 00:02:44.020
But if you see it
go up to like 2,

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.005
your eyes can tell you
in time that oh, it

00:02:47.005 --> 00:02:50.050
seems to be going up
pretty rapidly here.

00:02:50.050 --> 00:02:52.765
And so you'll see it maybe
go for 2.3 sometimes,

00:02:52.765 --> 00:02:54.460
and then drop back down.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:56.380
And that's kind of unusual.

00:02:56.380 --> 00:02:59.002
That's like, OK, there's
probably something around here.

00:02:59.002 --> 00:03:00.460
And then every once
in a while, you

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:04.780
might see something that goes
up further, 3, 3 and 1/2,

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:08.710
and those are like
definite leaks.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.490
AUDIENCE: What's the highest
number you've ever seen?

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:14.560
PROFESSOR: Well, in
DC, we got I think very

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:17.350
near to 100 parts per million.

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:19.450
And that's in the air
that we're breathing,

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:22.040
so it's not explosive
at that level.

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:26.260
But it's like 50 times more
than the background value.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:28.300
AUDIENCE: So 2 is baseline
kind of background.

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:30.008
PROFESSOR: Yeah, yeah,
you can consider 2

00:03:30.008 --> 00:03:32.260
to be a baseline level.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:41.980
Now it's like CO2, well, it used
to be 280 parts per million,

00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:44.320
and now it's like over 400.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:48.710
So 2 parts per million
methane is the new normal.

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:52.450
I mean it was 0.7 parts
per million, preindustrial.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:55.090
So I would like
to point that out

00:03:55.090 --> 00:03:59.180
that are our normal
baseline is very abnormal.

00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:01.680
So we're going up
about that with leaks.

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:04.270
Now this is a timeline
here, this graph,

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:08.590
and you can see as I came
in here, we did get 6, 7,

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:10.540
we got a few leaks here.

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:12.820
And that was right at the
Allston/Brighton tolls

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.610
coming down off
of the Mass Pike.

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:18.820
There's a leak there.

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:21.000
AUDIENCE: So what happens
in terms the reporting

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.650
that or following up with it?

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:26.200
PROFESSOR: So we don't
have any evidence,

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:28.270
but based on driving by.

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:33.550
We can't say whether it's
a green one hazardous leak,

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:38.530
a grade two, or a grade three
so-called non-hazardous leak.

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:42.040
So I don't feel
obligated that each

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:44.590
what we see that OK, we got
to call the gas company.

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:48.160
First of all, they do
know about these leaks.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:53.900
They know-- to a large
degree where they are.

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:56.680
But if we get out, and we
could, because we have the CGI.

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.770
If we decide to get out and
poke around and look through it,

00:04:59.770 --> 00:05:03.520
and we find evidence that
it is like a grade one,

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:07.896
then that's when I feel
obligated to call the leak in.

00:05:07.896 --> 00:05:09.670
'Cause it's like
we have knowledge

00:05:09.670 --> 00:05:14.070
that something
seems to be unsafe,

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:15.733
and so then we call it in.

00:05:15.733 --> 00:05:16.233
Yep?

00:05:16.233 --> 00:05:17.732
AUDIENCE: Is there
a clear indicator

00:05:17.732 --> 00:05:19.180
when it's a grade one?

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:20.740
PROFESSOR: This
machine is not going

00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:23.860
to be able to tell us whether
there's a grade one, a grade

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:27.230
explosive hazard, grade
two, or grade three.

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:34.510
And that's because you can
have big leaks with lots of gas

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:38.320
coming out that are
not explosive hazards.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:41.480
Like the Porter
Ranch gas leak in LA,

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:44.800
Audrey makes this point
a lot, it was technically

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:47.090
a grade three
non-hazardous leak,

00:05:47.090 --> 00:05:49.970
'cause it wasn't
going to explode.

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:52.180
And it wasn't that close
to the neighborhood,

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:54.610
it was like a quarter mile
away from the neighborhood.

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:57.700
So it's an indication
that that grading scheme

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:00.430
is only a single
variable grading scheme.

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:04.315
And explosion and
hazard is a big deal.

00:06:04.315 --> 00:06:06.440
There's no doubt about
that, and no one wants that.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:12.070
So what the grading
scheme has to incorporate

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:13.510
the amount of the flux.

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:15.910
There is a GPS on
this roof right now,

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:18.185
and it's plugged into
the back of the machine,

00:06:18.185 --> 00:06:22.375
and the data file that comes out
is already integrated with GPS

00:06:22.375 --> 00:06:23.765
with the time stamp.

00:06:23.765 --> 00:06:25.040
Straight?

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.554
AUDIENCE: Left, if we can, yep.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:34.250
So what are the
objectives for today?

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:40.680
Is it just to see how
methane is measured,

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:44.600
or are we trying to answer
any particular questions?

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:48.140
PROFESSOR: So what we call
this is a gas leak safari.

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:50.480
So one of the objectives--

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:55.590
OK, here we are, 2, 3, 2, 3,
so there's something there.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:02.090
So just to educate
and to show first

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:06.560
of all what this process is
of mapping the gas leaks.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:10.160
I think that we're going to
places that we have surveyed

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:15.530
in the past, Audrey and Heat did
the study now, two years ago,

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:17.810
is it?

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:19.334
But things change.

00:07:19.334 --> 00:07:20.500
AUDIENCE: Take a right here.

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:22.430
PROFESSOR: Right on Portland.

00:07:22.430 --> 00:07:26.634
2.1, 2.1, OK, here we
have something, 2.1.

00:07:26.634 --> 00:07:28.050
So there's something
here I think.

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:28.633
AUDIENCE: 2.3.

00:07:28.633 --> 00:07:29.270
AUDIENCE: 2.5.

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:29.862
2.7.

00:07:29.862 --> 00:07:31.320
PROFESSOR: OK,
yeah, read them out.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:32.980
AUDIENCE: 2.8.

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:39.082
PROFESSOR: OK, so there's a
leak here in this facility.

00:07:39.082 --> 00:07:41.537
AUDIENCE: Portland and Main.

00:07:41.537 --> 00:07:43.010
AUDIENCE: So that's at 2.3.

00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:47.066
Oh, 3.3, well, 4.4, 4.4.

00:07:47.066 --> 00:07:48.064
AUDIENCE: 4.2.

00:07:48.064 --> 00:07:49.635
3.8.

00:07:49.635 --> 00:07:51.010
PROFESSOR: So you
can see there's

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:53.210
the spike on the leading edge.

00:07:57.210 --> 00:07:57.710
Right?

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:06.530
It's really as you can imagine,
as any lay person can imagine,

00:08:06.530 --> 00:08:09.610
the vagaries of wind
are going to the plume.

00:08:09.610 --> 00:08:12.500
The plume is coming out of
wherever it can come out.

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.780
I could come out of
a man hole slot--

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:15.454
straight on?

00:08:15.454 --> 00:08:16.370
AUDIENCE: Straight on.

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:19.220
PROFESSOR: It could
come out of the soil.

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:21.990
A leak is going to to just
find whatever parallel

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:24.590
pathways it can get out.

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:26.750
And so you can
imagine, at the surface

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:31.760
there's some kind of profile
of this stuff coming out.

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:35.059
And then the wind's going to
carry it and blow it around.

00:08:35.059 --> 00:08:40.309
And so that makes
it a little tough.

00:08:40.309 --> 00:08:43.490
We can't really
pinpoint exactly where

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:45.220
it's coming out of the ground.

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:48.000
We can know when we
have driven by it.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.150
There's a leak in this
vicinity, and I would always

00:08:50.150 --> 00:08:54.140
say within 50 to
100 feet of where

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:57.660
we measured it is probably
part of the source coming

00:08:57.660 --> 00:08:59.030
on the ground.

00:08:59.030 --> 00:09:03.480
But to actually really pinpoint
where the pipeline leak is

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:06.480
would require stopping, getting
out, and using the instrument

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:10.290
that Audrey has as well as
maybe some other instruments,

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:15.950
handheld snippers to really
find out where it's coming out.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:21.140
What you're realizing right
now that makes it like discreet

00:09:21.140 --> 00:09:26.030
when we see a leak, if you
look at this timeline here,

00:09:26.030 --> 00:09:29.870
this trace, you can see
there's a lot of flat

00:09:29.870 --> 00:09:33.680
and then some fairly
well resolved spikes.

00:09:33.680 --> 00:09:38.450
And so it's not very
ambiguous when you get

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:40.820
an elevated anomalous reading.

00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:43.940
It's like, oh, there's one,
there's one, there's one.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:46.450
Here's a couple that are
small, but they really

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:50.190
need to go very clearly
from the back ground.

00:09:50.190 --> 00:09:53.300
So there's not that much
ambiguity about like, well,

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:57.525
is this kind of giant
blob a leak or not?

00:09:57.525 --> 00:10:02.205
They're well resolved
spikes in time and space.

00:10:02.205 --> 00:10:03.580
AUDIENCE: What's
the biggest leak

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:06.205
you've seen in the Boston area?

00:10:06.205 --> 00:10:09.550
PROFESSOR: Maybe like 40 or 50
parts per million in the air.

00:10:09.550 --> 00:10:11.811
AUDIENCE: Where was that?

00:10:11.811 --> 00:10:14.310
PROFESSOR: Well, a couple of
places that were close to that.

00:10:14.310 --> 00:10:21.700
One was Sullivan Square,
Rutherford Street

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:24.760
in Charles Town, kind of on
the Somerville Charles Town

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:26.480
border, the giant rotary.

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:27.210
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:10:27.210 --> 00:10:28.960
PROFESSOR: I mean, we
could go over there,

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:30.250
there is a big leak there.

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:33.313
And then Nonantum Road between
kind of Watertown and Newton.

00:10:33.313 --> 00:10:37.248
2.2, 2.3, OK, so there's
something here, OK.

00:10:37.248 --> 00:10:39.470
2.3, OK, so we've got, 2.5.

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:40.782
AUDIENCE: 2.5.

00:10:40.782 --> 00:10:41.674
AUDIENCE: 2.8.

00:10:41.674 --> 00:10:42.803
3.

00:10:42.803 --> 00:10:43.610
3.2.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:45.482
4.8.

00:10:45.482 --> 00:10:46.450
AUDIENCE: 6.

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:47.980
AUDIENCE: Oh boy.

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:48.817
Oh boy.

00:10:48.817 --> 00:10:49.400
AUDIENCE: 5.3.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:52.220
PROFESSOR: So I mean, we
could get out and take a break

00:10:52.220 --> 00:10:54.230
and find it if you
wanted on this one.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:55.520
It's kind of quiet.

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:58.340
This is definitely a
much blunter instrument

00:10:58.340 --> 00:10:59.690
than that one.

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:05.640
And it's made to find out
like percent level, 50%, 10%,

00:11:05.640 --> 00:11:07.146
not parts per million.

00:11:07.146 --> 00:11:09.790
OK, so this is now when
you want to find out

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:14.198
where is it coming out at, OK?

00:11:14.198 --> 00:11:18.272
The professionals right
now would have this bar,

00:11:18.272 --> 00:11:19.230
it's called a bang bar.

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:22.140
It's like one of those
construction pile drivers,

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:24.160
it's like a handheld
version of that.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:28.000
And you would find out,
maybe right here, you'd

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.800
like slam it down
maybe up to a meter.

00:11:32.800 --> 00:11:34.280
And this would have
a longer thing,

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:35.446
and you'd stick it in there.

00:11:35.446 --> 00:11:40.510
Now I don't do that, because
I'm not certified to do that,

00:11:40.510 --> 00:11:42.820
and I don't want to
puncture any gas lines

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:44.590
and create an explosion.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:49.720
So what I do is I just
kind of do like this,

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:53.220
and sometimes I'll use like
a screwdriver or just a stick

00:11:53.220 --> 00:11:56.440
even, and kind of--

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:58.870
this is right at the surface--

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:00.550
and poke around.

00:12:00.550 --> 00:12:04.740
So actually look, there
is something, point 0.2.

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:08.260
Now the fact, 0.25%.

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:16.250
So 0.25% is, let's see, 1%
is 10,000 parts per million,

00:12:16.250 --> 00:12:19.020
right, 1% is 10, 000
parts per million.

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:22.680
This is 8,500 parts
per million right now--

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:24.960
0.85, 0.9.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:29.040
OK, so the thing is that
this is right at the surface.

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:32.340
If I was down even
probably that much,

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:35.590
it would probably be
I don't know 15%, 20%.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:38.940
And if we went down a little
further, this could be 90% gas.

00:12:38.940 --> 00:12:44.750
See this is 0.25.

00:12:44.750 --> 00:12:46.370
Yeah, so about the same.

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:50.300
I'm just like about that far in.

00:12:50.300 --> 00:12:54.430
So this is an indication that
there's definitely a leak here.

00:12:54.430 --> 00:12:57.140
And it's no mistake we got
the 15 parts per million

00:12:57.140 --> 00:13:00.260
in the kind of air
that we're breathing.

00:13:00.260 --> 00:13:03.020
So now let's look around
for just infrastructure.

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:07.160
Let's see I mean, that was
a very arbitrary choice

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:07.970
of a place to look.

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:10.940
It's just we got
out, we're here.

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:13.500
But now I want to see like,
OK, where is the gas line?

00:13:13.500 --> 00:13:15.800
AUDIENCE: And all that.

00:13:15.800 --> 00:13:20.110
PROFESSOR: That could be a
vestige of a gas leak marking.

00:13:20.110 --> 00:13:23.240
And this big patch has
been for some purpose,

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:24.950
I don't know if
it was a gas line.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:26.930
I see some more
yellow paint out here.

00:13:29.870 --> 00:13:32.902
OK, so this is --

00:13:32.902 --> 00:13:37.040
OK, yeah, always be very
careful with the cars of course.

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:42.920
So this is a service line
